A. The Latin Bible.—Students are always pleased when some part of the day's lesson touches upon things in which they are ordinarily interested. You can make use of this characteristic by keeping a copy of the Latin New Testament on your desk, as it will be a means of awakenin g many a boy and turning to good account an hour that started off without promise. An English concordance at hand will help in finding these passages. Sometimes pupils will wish to commit passages to memory. In this case, place these passages on the blackboard.

The Beza edition of the New Testament and Psalms in Latin and the Latin Vulgate Bible may be ordered from any general bookstore. The Vulgate Bible is now under- going revision and the new edition will doubtless be available shortly.
